        <prj:TechnicalJustification>
            <prj:justificationText>To achieve the science goals outlined above, we propose to observe CO(2-1) spectral line toward the intersection of the dust bar/lanes and the circumnuclear starbust ring in the barred spiral galaxy NGC 1097 with ALMA with a 1" angular resolution. We have considered the feasibility of the proposed observation in the following aspects:

Angular Resolution: On the basis of previous observations, the circumnuclear starburst ring is ~20" in diameter and the bars/dust lanes is about 10" in width. The clumps in the bars/dust lanes is typically a few arcseconds in size. Thus the angular resolution of
1" will be adequate to distinguish the starburst ring and the bar/dust lane and resolved the dense clumps in the bar/dust lane.

Mosaic: To resolve the possible gas flows along the bars/dust lanes, we need to image the part of the bars/dust lanes relatively close to the starburst ring and thus request 8 points (4 points for each bar/dust lane) to cover regions ~25*65" along the two bar/dust lanes.

Spectral Resolution: The spectral resolution of 1.3 km/s is proposed. When analyzing the outer and weaker part of the bars/dust lanes, we will smooth the spectra to a resolution of ~10 km/s, which is suitable to distinguish the velocity gradient in gas flows for the systematic rotation and/or along the large-scale bars/dust lanes of NGC1097.

Sensitivity and Requested Time: With a beam size of 1.5*1.0" and a spectral resolution of 10 km/s, figures 4 and 5 of Hsien et al. (2011) indicate that the peak intensity of CO(2-1) spectrum is about 100 mJy/beam at their marked position D_3, where the dust lane is just about to connect/intersect the circumnuclear starburst ring. There are no high-resolution CO(2-1) observations for the outer part of the dust lanes/bars published, but we expect that the brightest regions of the outer bar/dust lane should have a similar CO(2-1) intensity to the D_3 position and the moderate bright ones have 20% of that intensity as indicated by the dust emissions in the far-infrared images of Herschel/PACS (at 70, 100, 160um; see Sandstrom et al. 2010). Thus in the proposed 1" resolution observations, we expect to detect the typical molecular clumps with a 20 mJy/beam flux density in the bars/dust lanes. On the other hand, the AOT gives that for proposed 6 obsreving points, an on-source time of 2.2 hours or total time of 4.1 hours would give a RMS noise of 1 mJy/beam in a 10km/s bandwith, adequate to detect the weaker clumps in the outer part of the bars/dust lanes. </prj:justificationText>
        </prj:TechnicalJustification>
